1679. Max Number of K-Sum Pairs
Problem

Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the maximum number of operations you can perform.

In one operation:

Choose two numbers whose sum equals k.
Remove them from the array.

Each element can be used only once.

Example
Input: nums = [1,2,3,4], k = 5
Output: 2

Explanation:

(1,4) and (2,3)
Approach 1: Brute Force
Intuition

For every element, search for another unused element whose sum equals k.

Use a boolean array to mark used elements.

Java
class Solution {
    public int maxOperations(int[] nums, int k) {

        boolean[] used = new boolean[nums.length];
        int count = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (used[i]) continue;

            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++) {

                if (!used[j] && nums[i] + nums[j] == k) {
                    used[i] = true;
                    used[j] = true;
                    count++;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,2,3,4]
k = 5
Pair	Used	Count
(1,4)	✓	1
(2,3)	✓	2

Answer:

2
Complexity
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(n)
Approach 2: HashMap (Optimal)
Intuition

For every number:

Need = k - num

If the needed number already exists, form a pair.

Otherwise, store the current number.

HashMap stores:

Number → Frequency
Algorithm
Traverse the array.
Compute complement = k - num.
If complement exists:
Form a pair.
Decrease complement frequency.
Otherwise:
Store current number.
Java
class Solution {
    public int maxOperations(int[] nums, int k) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        int count = 0;

        for (int num : nums) {

            int need = k - num;

            if (map.getOrDefault(need, 0) > 0) {

                count++;
                map.put(need, map.get(need) - 1);

            } else {

                map.put(num, map.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}
